docs.abstract: Article describes problems small NYC businesses face when they are in urban renewal area; Dr F Kristof, chief housing economist of NYS Urban Development Corp, says marginal businesses often fail; others are forced to make growth decisions and some that relocate do better but experience is usually 'devastating'; J Villanueva, HDA Relocation Comr, and his deputy, O Hogan, say that 612 businesses were displaced in 1972, with 28% going out of business as result; also say that if rundown neighborhoods were not renewed, many businesses would be lost anyway; some of small businessmen in Seward Park Extension Urban Renewal Area comment on problems they face; chances are that when Seward Park renewal is complete it will only contain about 20 stores, compared with 325 stores in 1964; diagram shows projects planned for renewal area; illus of some of small stores in area

headline.main: For Business, Urban Renewal Can Be Lethal; Urban Renewal Can Be Lethal
